<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="41" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="41">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="41">
Previously known only from Japan, this species is quite similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. bicolor" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" rank="species" species="bicolor">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">P. bicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the body colour pattern - head, pronotum, and abdominal segments 
<normalizedToken originalValue="VIII–X">VIII-X</normalizedToken>
brown. Specimens are identified here as 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. sasacola" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" rank="species" species="sasacola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="41">P. sasacola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have antennal segments 
<normalizedToken originalValue="III–IV">III-IV</normalizedToken>
each with two sense cones (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 7–16" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 7 - 16. Podothrips species. 7 - 10 Antenna 7 P. femoralis sp. nov. 8 P. odonaspicola 9 P. sasacola 10 P. semiflavus. 11, 12 Base of forewing 11 P. sasacola 12 P. femoralis sp. nov. Some important features of P. femoralis sp. nov. 13 mesopresternum 14 Pelta 15 abdominal tergites IV-V 16 abdominal tergites IX-X." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures7-16" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/349332" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures7-16">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
), and the fore tibia with a distinct inner apical tubercle (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 1–6" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figures 1 - 6. Podothrips species head, pronotum &amp; fore legs 1 P. femoralis sp. nov. 2 P. lucasseni 3 P. luteus (from Okajima 1978) 4 P. odonaspicola 5 P. sasacola 6 P. semiflavus." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures1-6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/349331" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.882.39029.figures1-6">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
) as described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Okajima, S" journalOrPublisher="Touka Shobo Co Ltd, Fukuoka" pageId="0" pageNumber="41" refId="B13" refString="Okajima, S, 2006. The Insects of Japan - Vol. 2 The Suborder Tubulifera (Thysanoptera). Touka Shobo Co Ltd, Fukuoka" title="The Insects of Japan - Vol. 2 The Suborder Tubulifera (Thysanoptera)." year="2006">Okajima (2006)</bibRefCitation>
. This species is recorded here for the first time from China, Sichuan, based on five males taken from reeds.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
